\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf4 There are 
\f0\b three 
\f1\b0 types of hormones: 
\f0\b peptide hormones, steroid hormones, 
\f1\b0 and 
\f0\b amino-acid derived hormones. 
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\

\f0\b \cb3 1. Peptide hormones (protein hormones): \
Synthesis - 
\f1\b0 produced in the 
\f0\b rough ER 
\f1\b0 and made of amino acids connected by 
\f3\i peptide bonds
\f1\i0 . \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Action - 
\f1\b0 binds to 
\f0\b cell surface receptors 
\f1\b0 because they 
\f3\i cannot 
\f1\i0 pass freely through the cell membrane as a result of being 
\f0\b water-soluble 
\f1\b0 (and 
\f3\i not 
\f1\i0 lipid-soluble). The process of hormone function is an 
\f0\b indirect stimulation
\f1\b0 . The two ways the signal can be received is through intracellular 
\f0\b secondary messengers 
\f1\b0 or 
\f0\b ligand-gated ion channels
\f1\b0 . \cb1 \
\

\f0\b \cb3 G protein coupled receptors (GPCRs) 
\f1\b0 are cell surface receptors that can initiate a 
\f0\b secondary messenger response 
\f1\b0 after binding to a peptide hormone extracellularly. A 
\f0\b G protein 
\f1\b0 is coupled to the receptor and dissociates into 
\f0\b subunits 
\f1\b0 (alpha (\uc0\u945 ), beta (\u946 ) and gamma (\u947 )) after activation. These subunits then act upon intracellular second messengers to propagate the signal. \

\f0\b Receptor tyrosine kinases (RTKs) 
\f1\b0 are another cell surface receptor that 
\f0\b dimerizes 
\f1\b0 and initiates 
\f0\b second messenger responses 
\f1\b0 upon binding to a peptide hormone (eg. insulin). The 
\f3\i intracellular 
\f1\i0 domains of RTKs 
\f0\b cross-phosphorylate 
\f1\b0 each other and initiate second messenger signaling 
\f3\i within 
\f1\i0 the cell. \cb1 \
\cb3 The 
\f0\b second messenger system 
\f1\b0 of peptide hormone signaling allows for 
\f0\b quick and immediate 
\f1\b0 physiological changes. \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Ligand-gated ion channels 
\f1\b0 change shape upon binding to peptide hormones, allowing 
\f0\b ions 
\f1\b0 to 
\f3\i flow 
\f1\i0 across the cell membrane. No second messengers are involved. \cb1 \
\

\f0\b \cb3 2. Steroid hormones:\cb1 \
\cb3 Synthesis - 
\f1\b0 produced in the 
\f0\b smooth ER 
\f1\b0 and made up of a fused 
\f3\i 4-ring 
\f1\i0 structure. \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Action 
\f1\b0 - requires a protein 
\f0\b carrier 
\f1\b0 to travel through the bloodstream due to being 
\f0\b lipophilic
\f1\b0 . Freely crosses the cell membrane, and binds to receptors either in the cytoplasm or the nucleus to form 
\f0\b molecule-receptor complexes 
\f1\b0 that bind to DNA, and influence gene transcription. This process is 
\f0\b direct stimulation
\f1\b0 . \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Examples 
\f1\b0 - all hormones produced by the 
\f0\b adrenal cortex 
\f1\b0 (glucocorticoids, mineralocorticoids, androgenic steroids) and 
\f0\b reproductive organs 
\f1\b0 (progesterone, testosterone, estrogen). \cb1 \
\

\f0\b \cb3 3. Amino-acid derived hormones: 
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\cb3 Can have properties that are similar to both 
\f3\i peptide 
\f1\i0 hormones and 
\f3\i steroid 
\f1\i0 hormones. \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Synthesis - 
\f1\b0 produced in 
\f0\b rough ER 
\f1\b0 and 
\f0\b cytosol. 
\f1\b0 Mainly derived from the amino acid 
\f0\b tyrosine. 
\f1\b0 \cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Examples - 
\f1\b0 all hormones produced by the 
\f0\b adrenal medulla 
\f1\b0 (epinephrine and norepinephrine, which are water-soluble). Also includes 
\f0\b T3 and T4 
\f1\b0 (lipid-soluble). \cb1 \
\
\
